The issue is missing backticks around the template literal. Template literals in JavaScript MUST use backticks (`), not quotes or no quotes.

❌ WRONG:
console.log(Text updated: "${value}");

✅ CORRECT:
console.log(`Text updated: "${value}"`);

Without backticks, this causes a syntax error.

The template literal is missing backticks. Here's the fix:

❌ WRONG:
console.log(The text is: ${text});

✅ CORRECT:
console.log(`The text is: ${text}`);

Template literals with ${} interpolation must be wrapped in backticks (`) to work correctly.
